<p><b>John Ronald Skirth</b> (11 December 1897 – 1977) served in the <a href="Royal_Garrison_Artillery" title="Royal Garrison Artillery">Royal Garrison Artillery</a> during the <a href="First_World_War" title="First World War" class="mw-redirect">First World War</a>. His experiences during the <a href="Battle_of_Messines_(1917)" title="Battle of Messines (1917)">Battle of Messines</a> and the <a href="Battle_of_Passchendaele" title="Battle of Passchendaele">Battle of Passchendaele</a> led him to resolve not to take human life, and for the rest of his army service he made deliberate errors in targeting calculations to try to ensure the guns of his battery missed their aiming point on the first attempt, giving the enemy a chance to evacuate. Many years later, after retiring from a career as a teacher, he wrote a memoir of his years in the army, describing his disillusionment with the conduct of the war and his conversion to <a href="Pacifism" title="Pacifism">pacifism</a>. In 2010 the memoir was published as <i><a href="The_Reluctant_Tommy" title="The Reluctant Tommy">The Reluctant Tommy</a></i>, edited by <a href="Duncan_Barrett" title="Duncan Barrett">Duncan Barrett</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-rel_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rel-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc">
<tr>
<td>
